prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: LBGs_z247DustContinuum
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Dust continuum observations of LBGs sitting in a z=2.47 Protocluster.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We are requesting a setup for continuum observations, and so do not request any custom setup for spectral resolution; we do not anticipate detection of any CO lines in the given setup (the nearest line is CO(9-8) which would likely not be detectable given estimates of it's line strength predicted by the average CO SLED of `normal' type galaxies like the Milky Way.

We request fairly low-resolution setup for ALMA, as we do not want to risk resolving out any of the flux which could be associated with dust continuum emission in each galaxy. To be safe, we request 1.5" resolution, which would result in beamsizes on order ~12kpc. 12kpc should fully encompass the angular scale of each galaxy (which we estimate should be ~8kpc at most, from work on resolved data in the optical, near-infrared, dust emission and CO dynamics of similar high-z galaxies). We has specified a largest angular scale of 2.5'' to accomodate possible extended dust emission in LBGs. However, this is unexpected.

Here we propose 870um (345GHz) continuum observations in band 7 for a sample of 35 LBGs in a z=2.47 proto-cluster. We estimate the continuum flux density of the sample at this wavelength is 0.25mJy based on a stack of submm single-dish data (from SCUBA-2; Casey et al. 2013) on the positions of these exact LBGs (Casey et al. 2015, Nature submitted). For a detection of at least 3sigma, we seek a target RMS of 80uJy. **This depth requires only 7 minutes on-source per target.**
The single dish estimates predict an average flux density of 0.25+-0.11mJy for LBGs in the protocluster, versus 0.11+-0.13mJy for LBGs outside the protocluster (in the field; see Figure 2 in the text). This is in-line with what we see from stacking experiments of much larger samples of LBGs at the same epoch (from single-dish; Coppin et al. 2015) and also from ALMA dust continuum of samples of LBGs in less dense environements from Cycle 0 and Cycle 2 programs led by Nick Scoville, looking at the ISM properties of normal, mass-selected galaxies in the COSMOS field from z~1-3. We intend on using this existing ALMA LBG sample (mass-matched and luminosity-matched to the LBGs in our structure) as a control sample. When sources are undetected in both samples, we intend to stack on the ALMA data to obtain a deeper estimate to the dust continuum level (which we are unable to do with existing confusion-limited single-dish data).
Note that these observations will take place at a rest-frame wavelength of 250um. This is safely in the Rayleigh-Jeans regime of the blackbody emission, although any shorter wavelengths would be cause for concern, as the blackbody would no longer be optically thin in that domain. We choose to stick to band 7 observations (instead of pushing to longer wavelengths in band 6 or band 3) because we have a firm estimate of the band 7 flux density and find it readily detectable, much more so than longer-wavelength observations in which the continuum flux will be substantially lower. To reiterate, the peak of the blackbody should sit at rest-frame wavelengths 70-100um for all LBGs, so it is certain that our rest-frame 250um observations are longward of the peak in a regime where flux density is directly proportional to dust mass.
The method we use to infer gas masses from dust continuum emission is demonstrated by Scoville et al. (2014; see also their cycle 0, 2, and proposed 3 observations). It is based on the fact that the measured dust-to-gas ratio in a wide variety of nearby galaxies (and a few out to high-redshift) is roughly constant, despite the huge range in luminosities, star-formation rates, and densities probed. In fact this dust-to-gas ratio seems to be more precise than extrapolating gas masses from high-J CO emission (which carries both the uncertainty in CO excitation and the CO-to-H2 conversion factor). Given that flux density measurements along the optically thin Rayleigh-Jeans tail provide an accurate estimate to dust mass (assuming some mass-weighted dust temperature of about 30K, which is not the same thing as the observed luminosity-weighted dust temperature seen in the SED), dust continuum flux densities provide accurate estimates to the total mass of gas (both atomic and molecular). And using local observations which demonstrate that M_H2 is roughly half of the total M_ISM, we therefore can calculate the mass of molecular hydrogen, M_H2, which is the fuel from which stars are formed.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract:
The identification of distant (z>2) massive galaxy proto-clusters has primarily focused on detection of faint Lyman-break galaxies (LBGs, or Lya emittors) around 1-3 bright radio-loud quasars or dusty starbursts. It is yet unknown how the lower-luminosity galaxies at these early epochs contribute to the growth of such massive structures. Are they growing at elevated rates with respect to similar galaxies in less dense environments? Or is their growth rate quenched with respect to the field? Current observational results are mixed: some claiming a reversal in the SFR-environment density relation at high-z, and others with no such evidence. The crucial missing part of the puzzle is those galaxies' gas supply, or potential for future star-formation, and the implications of such gas reservoirs on the star-formation histories of early proto-cluster galaxies.
Here we propose to observe 35 spectroscopically-confirmed LBGs in a remarkable z=2.47 proto-cluster in dust continuum to infer ISM masses thus gas masses. We will use those gas masses to infer the star-formation efficiency of galaxies in dense environments and compare against existing measurements for control galaxies in the field.
